This AWS "Show and Tell" video introduces AgentCore Observability, a dedicated suite of tools within Amazon Bedrock designed to monitor, track, and debug AI agents using open standards.Here is a comprehensive breakdown of the key concepts, architectures, and demonstrations discussed in the session:1. What is AgentCore Observability?Traditional applications follow deterministic paths (input $\rightarrow$ processing $\rightarrow$ output). However, AI agents are non-deterministic—they are given a goal and dynamically determine which APIs to call, what data to retrieve, and how to reason in production. Because they behave like a "black box," comprehensive visibility is essential.AgentCore Observability provides a unified glass pane to monitor agent applications by collecting and correlating the three pillars of telemetry:Logs: Tell you what happened.Traces: Tell you how it happened (the execution path).Metrics: Tell you how much or how well it happened (latencies, token counts, error rates).2. Core Architecture & OpenTelemetry StandardThe system is entirely decoupled and built on the OpenTelemetry (OTEL) framework, ensuring users are not locked into proprietary AWS tooling.Spans & Traces: Every individual action an agent takes (such as an LLM call or a web search tool execution) is packaged as a JSON object called a Span. A sequential chain of these spans constitutes a Trace, tied together by a unique Trace ID [23:36].Sessions: When a user interacts multiple times with a chat agent, the request-response cycles are grouped under a single Session ID [24:14].Distributed Tracing & Baggage: Agents often communicate with different microservices, microVMs, or external Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers. Using OTEL headers, the Trace ID is propagated across systems transparently. Custom metadata (like a tenant ID or business unit) can be passed across these application barriers using an OTEL feature called Baggage [36:34].AWS Integration: By default, data routes seamlessly through the AWS Distro for OpenTelemetry (ADOT) directly into Amazon CloudWatch metrics and a specialized log group called AWS spans [28:34].3. How to Set It UpThe speakers demonstrate that the setup process is minimal, split between the application framework and the runtime host environment [11:51]:One-Time Prerequisite: Enable Transaction Search within your AWS console [12:22].Environment Variables: Configure environment variables pointing to your designated CloudWatch log groups and streams, and name your target agent.Instrumentation Wrapper: Wrap your python execution using standard open-source library hooks (e.g., opentelemetry-instrument python agent.py) [14:54].The platform broadly supports popular open-source agent frameworks right out of the box (including Strands, LangGraph, and CrewAI), doing the heavy lifting of translating differing telemetry payloads into a unified dashboard [39:55].4. Advanced Demos & GovernanceThe latter half of the video features technical walkthroughs demonstrating complex agent tracking:Multi-Agent Systems: They showcase a hierarchical multi-agent structure built using both Strands and LangGraph distributed across three distinct runtimes. The system seamlessly tracks a single invocation as an orchestrator agent calls down to sub-agents, displaying a visual tree-view mapping the exact latency of each component [43:58].Resource Health: Aside from framework-level traces, the console shows infrastructure vended logs—tracking metrics specific to the AgentCore Gateway or short/long-term AgentCore Memory instances [18:07].Security & Guardrails: To address privacy concerns regarding proprietary data or PII leaking into logs, the team notes that users can leverage standard CloudWatch Data Protection Policies to redact or mask information at the log-group level automatically [33:05].5. Continuous ImprovementThe data gathered through AgentCore Observability directly fuels AgentCore Evaluations. In the final minutes, they display an integrated dashboard where builders can evaluate automated agent performance directly alongside historical trace latencies and session histories [58:27].